TY  - JOUR
T1  - Outsourcing Information Security: Contracting Issues and Security Implications
AU  - Cezar, Asunur
AU  - Cavusoglu, Huseyin
AU  - Raghunathan, Srinivasan
Y1  - 2013/09/27
PY  - 2013
DA  - 2014/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2013.1763
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2013.1763
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 638
EP  - 657
VL  - 60
IS  - 3
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - A unique challenge in information security outsourcing is that neither the outsourcing firm nor the managed security service provider (MSSP) perfectly observes the outcome, the occurrence of a security breach, of prevention effort. Detection of security breaches often requires specialized effort. The current practice is to outsource both prevention and detection to the same MSSP. Some security experts have advocated outsourcing prevention and detection to different MSSPs. We show that the former outsourcing contract leads to a significant disincentive to provide detection effort. The latter contract alleviates this problem but introduces misalignment of incentives between the firm and the MSSPs and eliminates the advantages offered by complementarity between prevention and detection functions, which may lead to a worse outcome than the current contract. We propose a new contract that is superior to these two on various dimensions. This paper was accepted by Lorin Hitt, information systems.
AB  - A unique challenge in information security outsourcing is that neither the outsourcing firm nor the managed security service provider (MSSP) perfectly observes the outcome, the occurrence of a security breach, of prevention effort. Detection of security breaches often requires specialized effort. The current practice is to outsource both prevention and detection to the same MSSP. Some security experts have advocated outsourcing prevention and detection to different MSSPs. We show that the former outsourcing contract leads to a significant disincentive to provide detection effort. The latter contract alleviates this problem but introduces misalignment of incentives between the firm and the MSSPs and eliminates the advantages offered by complementarity between prevention and detection functions, which may lead to a worse outcome than the current contract. We propose a new contract that is superior to these two on various dimensions. This paper was accepted by Lorin Hitt, information systems.
